CUME_DIST()/PERCENT_RANK() position is identified based on percentage of postion.
ROW_NUMBER,RANK() generate numberic number as rank, where as CUME_DIST/PERCENT_RANK generates percentage of positin of row 
based on sorting order.

6. CUME_DIST ==> CUME_DIST() OVER(ORDER BY sales DESC)
CUME_DIST = Position of Row/Number of Rows
PERCENT_RANK() = POSITION OF ROW -1/NUMBER OF ROWS -1
PERCENT_RANK() OVER (ORDER BY sales DESC) 

CUME_DIST is inclusive of current row where was PERCENT_RANK() exclusive of current row.

--find the products that fall within the highest 40% of the prices
SELECT *,CONCAT(distRank*100,'%') DIST FROM (
SELECT
Product,
Price,
CUME_DIST() OVER(ORDER BY PRICE DESC) distRank
FROM
Sales.Products
)t
WHERE distRank <=0.4


--find the products that fall within the highest 50% of the prices USING PERCENT_RANK
SELECT *,CONCAT(distRank*100,'%') DIST FROM (
SELECT
Product,
Price,
PERCENT_RANK() OVER(ORDER BY PRICE DESC) distRank
FROM
Sales.Products
)t
WHERE distRank <=0.5

7. NTILE(input as number) OVER(ORDER BY sales DESC)
==> Divides the rows into a specified number of approximately equal groups (Buckets)
Bucket size = No. of Rows/ Number of buckets(input as number)
SQL Rule ==> When we decimal point when handling bucket size always Larger group comes first.

SELECT
OrderID,
Sales,
NTILE(1) OVER (ORDER BY sales DESC) BUCKET1,
NTILE(2) OVER (ORDER BY sales DESC) BUCKET2,
NTILE(3) OVER (ORDER BY sales DESC) BUCKET3,
NTILE(4) OVER (ORDER BY sales DESC) BUCKET4
FROM Sales.Orders

i. Data Segmentation :- Divides a dataset into distinct subsets based on certain criteria

--segment all order into 3 categories :High,medium  and low sales
SELECT 
*,
CASE WHEN buckets=1 THEN 'High'
	 WHEN buckets=2 THEN 'Medium'
	 WHEN buckets=3 THEN 'Low' END
FROM (
	SELECT
	OrderID,
	Sales,
	NTILE(3) OVER(ORDER BY sales DESC) buckets
	FROM Sales.Orders
)t

2. Usecase - when table is big, split the table data to split into 4-5 buckets using NTILE(4) then combine using after data loading
which reduce network tranfic. 

--In order to export the data, divide the orders into 2 groups
SELECT
NTILE(2) OVER(ORDER BY orderid) buckets,
*
FROM Sales.Orders


